This small square located on the banks of the Seine provides access to the martyrs' memorial. This eastern part of the Ile de la Cit√© was for a long time devoid of any particular use. Called ‚ÄúMotte aux papelards‚Äù or ‚ÄúTerrain‚Äù until the 18th century, this place seems to have been the repository of numerous rubble, after the construction of Notre-Dame Cathedral, and accumulated rubbish. In 1687, a first walled garden was noted as accessible only to cathedral canons and men. Then, Prefect Haussmann had the capital's morgue built there between 1861-1863 by the architect √âmile Gilbert. The decision to move to Quai de la R√¢p√©e in 1914 allowed the creation, after destruction of the buildings, of a first square. It was in 1929 that it was baptized with its current name. The entrance to the Memorial of the Martyrs of Deportation takes place through the square. The construction of this monument-crypt from 1954 to 1964 by Georges-Henri Pingusson was an opportunity to rework the green spaces. A weeping willow is dedicated to the victims of Nazism and ‚ÄúResurrection‚Äù rose bushes pay tribute to the Resistance and the victims of deportation.
